the 1997 Green Revolution coordinated by the International Labour Organization to halve rural poverty by 2015. Since the introduction of the program, Togo has been focused on poverty reduction, mobilizing its resources to support the initiative among local communities and its production base.

At the end of 1998, Togo implemented a program to transform agriculture. This involved helping farmers acquire knowledge of modern farming methods, improving production and processing equipment and agricultural infrastructure, and supporting the marketing of agricultural products. As of the end of 2015, Togo's agricultural development had achieved a clear achievement.

Togo's development process is facing manyChallenges, such as increasing foreign exchange costs, widening income disparities between the haves and the have-nots, climate change effects, lack of agricultural infrastructure, etc., so a strong sense of global partnership and mutual assistance is critical forTogo's development. And Nigeria, the world's largest economy and Africa's largest oil producer, plays a key role. The future development of Togo and other African nations depends mainly on the support of developing countries, and to what extent the Nigerian economy grows depends mainly on the economic development of Togo.

Proactively innovate, and step forward

In the face of the above challenges, Togo is actively innovating policies and programs to promote continuous economic development. The country is now in good geographical location, alongside the Lake Togo, before the banks of the Keron River, with the Gulf of Ghana on its west coast
